<tool name="call_subagent">
  <description>Delegate a task to a sub-agent that answers by querying Phoenix's own data (projects, traces, spans, datasets, experiments, evaluations, and more).</description>
  <when_to_use>
    Use a sub-agent when answering a question can be answered querying Phoenix's data. The sub-agent does that work in its own context and returns only the answer you need. It has a `bash` tool that runs in a networkless, in-memory virtual file system (with scratch space under `/home/user/workspace` and standard utilities like `cat`, `grep`, `jq`, and `sqlite3`), and that `bash` includes `phoenix-gql` for running read-only GraphQL queries against the Phoenix schema in-process. It can also search the Phoenix documentation and the web when those tools are enabled.
  </when_to_use>
  <usage>Pass `task`, a single self-contained natural-language description of exactly what you need, along with `name`, a short human-readable name for the sub-agent.</usage>
  <important>The sub-agent won't have access to your context, so the task needs to be entirely self-contained and fully specified. It must explicitly pass along IDs, time ranges, and any other details rather than assuming they will be visible to the sub-agent.</important>
</tool>
